      "matchingRecords": [],
      "meetsCriteria": true,
      "result": {
        "justification": "Information was extracted from multiple clinical notes including ED attestation (06/08/2019), hematology consults (07/23/2019, 10/28/2019), nursing plans of care (2019), physical therapy assessment (11/24/2019), nutrition assessment (11/24/2019), and procedural notes (07/15/2020).",
        "other_pertinent_information": "The patient is an 80-year-old female with a longstanding history of chronic autoimmune hemolytic anemia diagnosed in 2012, status post splenectomy, who remains transfusion-dependent despite treatment with steroids, rituximab, and azathioprine. She has developed complications including iron overload requiring chelation therapy, iatrogenic Cushing's syndrome from steroid use, and worsening dementia possibly related to iron overload or Alzheimer's disease. The patient has undergone multiple hospital admissions for severe anemia requiring frequent red blood cell transfusions complicated by warm autoantibodies making blood matching difficult. She has a history of hypertension, hyperlipidemia, GERD, hysterectomy, hernia repair, and right shoulder surgery, and has a port for frequent blood draws which was removed in 2020. Recent evaluations include physical therapy for impaired mobility and balance, nutrition assessment for inadequate intake and weight loss, and echocardiogram showing normal ejection fraction. She lives at home with her husband and has family support, including a daughter who is a nurse and assists with care. Recent preventive screenings include a colonoscopy in 2013 and mammogram status is not explicitly documented."
      }
    },
